1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,419
Today, I want to tell you about one of my favorite stories

2
00:00:04,419 --> 00:00:07,662
in mathematics: the Basel Problem — a sum that resisted

3
00:00:07,662 --> 00:00:11,140
solution for eighty-five years before a young mathematician

4
00:00:11,140 --> 00:00:14,087
finally cracked it with a beautifully simple idea.

5
00:00:15,587 --> 00:00:17,338
Here's the question.

6
00:00:17,338 --> 00:00:24,164
Take every perfect square — one, four, nine, sixteen, twenty-five, and so on —

7
00:00:24,164 --> 00:00:27,665
flip each one over, and add them all up.

8
00:00:27,665 --> 00:00:32,828
Does this infinite sum converge? And if it does... to what?

9
00:00:34,328 --> 00:00:38,883
The problem was first posed by Pietro Mengoli in 1650.

10
00:00:38,883 --> 00:00:41,245
Now, the sum does converge —

11
00:00:41,245 --> 00:00:47,572
you can check that by comparing it with the integral of one over x squared.

12
00:00:47,572 --> 00:00:54,236
Add up the first hundred terms, you get about 1.6349. A thousand terms? 1.6439.

13
00:00:54,236 --> 00:01:00,310
It's clearly approaching something near 1.6449. But what is this number?

14
00:01:00,310 --> 00:01:05,540
Is it the root of some polynomial? The logarithm of something?

15
00:01:05,540 --> 00:01:07,817
Nobody could figure it out.

16
00:01:09,317 --> 00:01:14,998
Even Jakob Bernoulli, one of the greatest mathematicians of his era,

17
00:01:14,998 --> 00:01:17,003
admitted defeat in 1689.

18
00:01:17,003 --> 00:01:17,755
He wrote:

19
00:01:19,255 --> 00:01:23,541
"If anyone finds and communicates to us that which thusfar

20
00:01:23,541 --> 00:01:27,457
has eluded our efforts, great will be our gratitude."

21
00:01:28,957 --> 00:01:32,036
For eighty-five years, nobody could solve it.

22
00:01:32,036 --> 00:01:36,005
Then in 1734, a twenty-seven year old named Leonard Euler,

23
00:01:36,005 --> 00:01:40,999
working at the Academy of Sciences in Saint Petersburg, found the answer.

24
00:01:40,999 --> 00:01:43,873
He presented his proof the following year.

25
00:01:45,373 --> 00:01:49,251
The sum equals pi squared over six. And that was shocking.

26
00:01:49,251 --> 00:01:53,329
Pi is the ratio of a circle's circumference to its diameter —

27
00:01:53,329 --> 00:01:57,408
why on earth would it show up in a sum of reciprocal squares?

28
00:01:57,408 --> 00:02:02,690
There's no circle anywhere in sight. Let me show you Euler's original argument.

29
00:02:02,690 --> 00:02:05,631
It's not fully rigorous by modern standards,

30
00:02:05,631 --> 00:02:10,445
but the intuition is so compelling that everyone accepted it right away,

31
00:02:10,445 --> 00:02:14,056
and the gaps got filled in over the following century.

32
00:02:15,556 --> 00:02:20,910
Euler's proof starts with something you might not expect — the sine function.

33
00:02:20,910 --> 00:02:23,691
We know the Taylor series for sine of x:

34
00:02:23,691 --> 00:02:26,612
it's x minus x cubed over three factorial,

35
00:02:26,612 --> 00:02:30,158
plus x to the fifth over five factorial, and so on.

36
00:02:31,658 --> 00:02:36,686
Now remember, an infinite series is just a limit of partial sums.

37
00:02:36,686 --> 00:02:41,017
For any fixed nonzero x, we can divide that limit by x —

38
00:02:41,017 --> 00:02:44,730
that's justified by the algebraic limit theorem.

39
00:02:44,730 --> 00:02:49,602
So we get sine of x over x equals one minus x squared over six,

40
00:02:49,602 --> 00:02:51,459
plus higher-order terms.

41
00:02:52,959 --> 00:02:57,476
Hold onto that coefficient of x squared — it's negative one-sixth.

42
00:02:57,476 --> 00:02:59,803
That number is going to come back.

43
00:03:01,303 --> 00:03:07,200
Now here's Euler's bold move — the step that made this proof famous.

44
00:03:07,200 --> 00:03:13,531
The function sine of x over x equals zero whenever x is plus or minus pi,

45
00:03:13,531 --> 00:03:18,387
plus or minus two pi, plus or minus three pi, and so on.

46
00:03:19,887 --> 00:03:21,942
Euler reasoned by analogy.

47
00:03:21,942 --> 00:03:27,871
If a polynomial has certain roots, you can factor it as a product of terms,

48
00:03:27,871 --> 00:03:29,293
one for each root.

49
00:03:29,293 --> 00:03:33,009
He applied the same logic to sine of x over x —

50
00:03:33,009 --> 00:03:37,672
even though it's not a polynomial, it's an infinite series.

51
00:03:37,672 --> 00:03:40,439
He wrote it as an infinite product,

52
00:03:40,439 --> 00:03:44,312
where each factor corresponds to a pair of roots.

53
00:03:44,312 --> 00:03:47,553
Now, this was an assumption, not a proof.

54
00:03:47,553 --> 00:03:50,952
The rigorous justification came much later,

55
00:03:50,952 --> 00:03:54,983
with the Weierstrass factorization theorem of 1876.

56
00:03:54,983 --> 00:03:56,406
So what do we get?

57
00:03:57,906 --> 00:04:00,635
Before we tackle the infinite product,

58
00:04:00,635 --> 00:04:03,652
let's see why this works for a finite one.

59
00:04:03,652 --> 00:04:09,254
Take just three factors. Each factor looks like one minus a-k times x squared.

60
00:04:09,254 --> 00:04:12,415
When we multiply them out, an x-squared term

61
00:04:12,415 --> 00:04:15,216
only shows up when we pick the negative

62
00:04:15,216 --> 00:04:20,962
a-k x-squared piece from exactly one factor and the one from every other factor.

63
00:04:20,962 --> 00:04:24,553
Pick the x-squared piece from two or more factors,

64
00:04:24,553 --> 00:04:27,282
and you get x to the fourth or higher.

65
00:04:27,282 --> 00:04:32,741
So the x-squared coefficient is just the sum, a-one plus a-two plus a-three,

66
00:04:32,741 --> 00:04:34,033
with a minus sign.

67
00:04:35,533 --> 00:04:38,355
Now extend this to the infinite product.

68
00:04:38,355 --> 00:04:40,472
By exactly the same reasoning,

69
00:04:40,472 --> 00:04:45,551
the x-squared coefficient is the sum of all the a-k's with a minus sign.

70
00:04:45,551 --> 00:04:50,772
That gives us negative one over pi squared, plus one over four pi squared,

71
00:04:50,772 --> 00:04:53,664
plus one over nine pi squared, and so on.

72
00:04:53,664 --> 00:04:59,097
Factor out the one over pi squared, and what's left? Exactly our mystery sum.

73
00:04:59,097 --> 00:05:03,471
Now, extending the finite argument to an infinite product does

74
00:05:03,471 --> 00:05:07,986
require absolute convergence and a valid power series expansion.

75
00:05:07,986 --> 00:05:11,866
That's true here, but it wasn't proven in Euler's time.

76
00:05:11,866 --> 00:05:13,629
Granting that assumption,

77
00:05:13,629 --> 00:05:17,721
the extraction works just as it does for a finite product.

78
00:05:19,221 --> 00:05:20,278
Now we compare.

79
00:05:20,278 --> 00:05:25,491
The Taylor series told us the x squared coefficient is negative one-sixth.

80
00:05:26,991 --> 00:05:29,262
And the infinite product told us it's

81
00:05:29,262 --> 00:05:31,902
negative one over pi squared times our sum.

82
00:05:33,402 --> 00:05:36,599
Both are power series for the same function,

83
00:05:36,599 --> 00:05:39,797
and a power series representation is unique.

84
00:05:39,797 --> 00:05:42,268
So the coefficients have to match.

85
00:05:42,268 --> 00:05:48,082
Set them equal, and you get: one over pi squared times the sum equals one-sixth.

86
00:05:49,582 --> 00:05:53,912
Multiply both sides by pi squared, and there it is.

87
00:05:53,912 --> 00:06:00,195
One plus one-fourth plus one-ninth plus one-sixteenth, and so on forever —

88
00:06:00,195 --> 00:06:02,742
it equals pi squared over six.

89
00:06:02,742 --> 00:06:08,854
That mysterious 1.6449 that nobody could pin down for eighty-five years?

90
00:06:08,854 --> 00:06:15,052
Pi squared over six. The circle constant was hiding in the sum all along.

91
00:06:16,552 --> 00:06:22,341
So should we worry that Euler's proof cut corners? Mathematicians certainly did.

92
00:06:22,341 --> 00:06:25,959
It took over a century before Weierstrass provided

93
00:06:25,959 --> 00:06:29,359
the tools to make that factoring step rigorous.

94
00:06:29,359 --> 00:06:31,820
But the answer was never in doubt.

95
00:06:31,820 --> 00:06:34,786
Sometimes intuition runs ahead of proof —

96
00:06:34,786 --> 00:06:38,260
and that gap is where new mathematics gets born.

97
00:06:39,760 --> 00:06:44,193
What we just computed is actually a special value of what

98
00:06:44,193 --> 00:06:48,549
we now call the Riemann zeta function — at s equals two.

99
00:06:48,549 --> 00:06:53,838
Euler himself went on to show that all the even values, zeta of two,

100
00:06:53,838 --> 00:06:59,828
zeta of four, zeta of six, and so on, are rational multiples of powers of pi.

101
00:06:59,828 --> 00:07:04,728
But the odd values? Zeta of three, zeta of five, zeta of seven?

102
00:07:04,728 --> 00:07:06,050
Still mysterious.

103
00:07:06,050 --> 00:07:10,951
To this day, nobody's found clean closed forms for any of them.

104
00:07:10,951 --> 00:07:14,684
Some of the biggest open problems in mathematics

105
00:07:14,684 --> 00:07:18,029
trace right back to this one beautiful sum.

106
00:07:19,529 --> 00:07:20,894
So what did we learn?

107
00:07:20,894 --> 00:07:25,054
Sometimes a simple question — one you could explain to a child —

108
00:07:25,054 --> 00:07:27,590
hides an answer of extraordinary depth.

109
00:07:27,590 --> 00:07:30,385
Euler's genius wasn't just technical skill.

110
00:07:30,385 --> 00:07:34,480
It was the boldness to try something that had no right to work,

111
00:07:34,480 --> 00:07:37,600
and the taste to recognize beauty in the result.

112
00:07:37,600 --> 00:07:42,541
And at the heart of it all is pi, quietly connecting the geometry of circles

113
00:07:42,541 --> 00:07:47,286
to the arithmetic of whole numbers in ways we're still discovering today.

114
00:07:47,286 --> 00:07:50,471
Thanks for joining me on this journey through one

115
00:07:50,471 --> 00:07:53,331
of the most beautiful proofs in mathematics.
